{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17638746","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17638746"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:58:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:58:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17732"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17732","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17732"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.05,0.05,0.05,0.81]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10446"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77669"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10446","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10446"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17732"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63182"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5221"},{"type":"tags","id":"10330"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24392"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24393"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77669","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77669"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA physician discusses potential treatment options for a patient\u0027s pain, including a class of drugs known for their analgesic ability, which correlates to Mu-receptor binding.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following classes of drugs is being described?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Antipyretic analgesics","Antidepressants","Anticonvulsants","Cannabinoids","Opioids"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe class of drugs being described is \u003Cstrong\u003Eopioids\u003C/strong\u003E. Opioids are well-known for their analgesic properties, which are primarily mediated through binding to Mu-opioid receptors in the central nervous system. This binding leads to a reduction in the perception of pain, making opioids effective for managing moderate to severe pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAntipyretic analgesics\u003C/strong\u003E, such as paracetamol and non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs), work through different mechanisms, primarily involving the inhibition of cyclooxygenase enzymes, and do not primarily target Mu-receptors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAntidepressants\u003C/strong\u003E can be used for pain management, particularly in chronic pain syndromes, but their mechanism involves modulation of neurotransmitters like serotonin and noradrenaline, not Mu-receptor binding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnticonvulsants\u003C/strong\u003E are sometimes used in pain management, especially for neuropathic pain, but they work by stabilising neuronal membranes and modulating ion channels, not through Mu-receptors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECannabinoids\u003C/strong\u003E interact with the endocannabinoid system, primarily through CB1 and CB2 receptors, and do not exert their effects through Mu-opioid receptors.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Opioids exert their analgesic effects primarily through binding to Mu-opioid receptors.","Mu-receptor binding is a key mechanism in the pain-relieving properties of opioids.","Understanding receptor binding is crucial in pharmacology for predicting drug effects."],"references":["Queremel Milani DA, Davis DD. Pain Management Medications. [Updated 2023 Jul 3]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK560692/","Valentino RJ, Volkow ND. Untangling the complexity of opioid receptor function. Neuropsychopharmacology. 2018 Dec;43(13):2514-2520. doi: 10.1038/s41386-018-0225-3. Epub 2018 Sep 24. PMID: 30250308; PMCID: PMC6224460.","Contet C, Kieffer BL, Befort K. Mu opioid receptor: a gateway to drug addiction. Curr Opin Neurobiol. 2004 Jun;14(3):370-8. doi: 10.1016/j.conb.2004.05.005. PMID: 15194118.","Al-Hasani R, Bruchas MR. Molecular mechanisms of opioid receptor-dependent signaling and behavior. Anesthesiology. 2011 Dec;115(6):1363-81. doi: 10.1097/ALN.0b013e318238bba6. PMID: 22020140; PMCID: PMC3698859."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63182"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17732"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63182","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63182"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-07T21:28:54+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-08T00:06:07+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10446"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77669"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms